<handout>
<title>Daily Prep 5.6 - Second Order Systems and Applications</title>

<section>
    <title>Overview</title>
<p>
We now introduce second-order systems of differential equations, with a 
central focus on physical applications such as undamped mass–spring systems. 
Instead of rewriting these problems as large first-order systems, the section 
treats them directly in their natural second-order form, where the displacement 
vector <m>\vec{x}</m> satisfies an equation of the type <m>M \vec{x}'' = K \vec{x}</m>, 
with <m>M</m> the mass matrix and <m>K</m> the stiffness matrix.  Using Hooke’s 
law and Newton’s second law, the dynamics of several coupled masses can be 
expressed compactly in matrix notation, revealing structural patterns that 
generalize to an arbitrary number of masses.  Because <m>M</m> is diagonal and 
invertible, the system can be rewritten as <m>\vec{x}'' = M^{-1} K \vec{x}</m>, 
which leads to oscillatory behavior governed by the eigenvalues and eigenvectors 
of <m>M^{-1}K</m>.  The section highlights how these ideas connect discrete 
mass–spring models to continuum models such as the wave equation, showing how 
second-order systems arise naturally in many physical contexts. 
</p>

</section>

