<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise label="mcqsecondordersetup">
  <title>Setting Up a Second-Order System</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      In the three‑mass spring system, which equation
      correctly represents the mathematical model obtained from Newton’s second
      law and Hooke’s law?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>M \vec{x}'' = K \vec{x}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The section derives the system 
          <m>M \vec{x}'' = K \vec{x}</m>, where <m>M</m> is the mass matrix 
          and <m>K</m> is the stiffness matrix.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>M \vec{x}' = K \vec{x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this would describe a first‑order system, not a second‑order one.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>K \vec{x}'' = M \vec{x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—Newton’s law leads to mass times acceleration on the left.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqsecondorderinversion">
  <title>Inverting the Mass Matrix</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Why is it easy to compute <m>M^{-1}</m> for the mass matrix <m>M</m> in
      these models?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Because <m>M</m> is diagonal with nonzero entries.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Each mass is nonzero, and <m>M</m> is diagonal, so 
          <m>M^{-1}</m> is obtained by inverting each diagonal entry.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Because <m>M = I</m> for any mass–spring system.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. The diagonal entries are the masses, not ones.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Because <m>M</m> is symmetric.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Symmetry alone does not make inversion easy; diagonal form does.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqsecondordereigen">
  <title>Meaning of <m>M^{-1}K</m></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      After rewriting the system as 
      <m>\vec{x}'' = M^{-1} K \vec{x}</m>, 
      what is the significance of the matrix <m>M^{-1}K</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Its eigenvalues determine the natural frequencies of the system.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The section explains that the eigenvalues of 
          <m>M^{-1}K</m> give the oscillation frequencies (normal modes)
          of the mass–spring system.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>It measures how quickly the masses grow without bound.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. The system models oscillations, not exponential growth.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement>
        <p>It determines whether <m>M</m> is invertible.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>No. <m>M</m> is invertible because the masses are nonzero.</p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqsecondordercomputeMinvK1">
  <title>Computing One Entry of <m>M^{-1}K</m></title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider a two‑mass system with
      <m>
        M =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          2 \amp 0 \\
          0 \amp 3
        \end{bmatrix},
        K =
        \begin{bmatrix}
          -5 \amp 4 \\
          4 \amp -6
        \end{bmatrix}.
      </m>
      What is the <m>(1,2)</m> entry of <m>M^{-1}K</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>2</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. 
          <m>M^{-1} = \begin{bmatrix} \tfrac{1}{2} \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp \tfrac{1}{3} \end{bmatrix}</m>,
          so the <m>(1,2)</m> entry is 
          <m>\tfrac{1}{2} \cdot 4 = 2</m>.
          This matches how second‑order systems become 
          <m>\vec{x}'' = M^{-1}K \vec{x}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>4</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this is the <m>(1,2)</m> entry of <m>K</m>, not <m>M^{-1}K</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice><statement><p><m>\tfrac{4}{3}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—the second row would use <m>\tfrac{1}{3}</m>, not the first.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcqsecondordereigenvaluesign">
  <title>Interpreting a Computed Eigenvalue</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose a second‑order system
      <m>\vec{x}'' = M^{-1}K \vec{x}</m>
      for some two‑mass model yields an eigenvalue 
      <m>\lambda = -9</m>.
      What does this tell you about the behavior of the mode corresponding
      to this eigenvalue?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>The mode oscillates with natural frequency <m>3</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. For <m>\vec{x}'' = \lambda \vec{x}</m>, a negative 
          <m>\lambda</m> produces oscillations with frequency 
          <m>\sqrt{-\lambda} = 3</m>.  
          The section explains how eigenvalues of <m>M^{-1}K</m> encode
          natural frequencies.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The mode grows exponentially without bound.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. Exponential growth occurs when <m>\lambda>0</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>The mode decays exponentially to zero.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No. Negative eigenvalues in this setup produce oscillations, not decay.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>


  <!-- PROBLEM 1 -->
  <exercise xml:id="secondorderopennew1">
    <title>Energy Interpretation of a Second-Order System</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider a second-order system of the form 
        <m>M \vec{x}'' = K \vec{x}</m>, where <m>M</m> is the mass matrix 
        and <m>K</m> is the stiffness matrix of an undamped mass–spring 
        system. 
      </p>
      <p>
        (a) Explain why this system conserves mechanical energy when there is 
        no damping.  
        <br/>
        (b) Describe the physical meaning of the matrices <m>M</m> and 
        <m>K</m> in terms of kinetic and potential energy.
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        <strong>(a)</strong>  
        In an undamped mass–spring system, no forces remove energy from the 
        system. The springs store <em>potential energy</em> and the masses 
        carry <em>kinetic energy</em>, and energy simply transfers back and 
        forth between these two forms.  
        The equation <m>M \vec{x}'' = K \vec{x}</m> results from applying 
        Newton’s second law and Hooke’s law to the system, and because no 
        damping forces are present, the total mechanical energy
      </p>

      <me>
        E(t) = \tfrac12 (\vec{x}')^{\!T} M \vec{x}' 
              + \tfrac12 \vec{x}^{T} K \vec{x}
      </me>

      <p>
        remains constant.  
        This conservation reflects exactly the behavior of the undamped 
        multi-mass system.  
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>(b)</strong>  
        The matrix <m>M</m> represents the distribution of <em>inertia</em> 
        in the system. Because it is diagonal with entries <m>m_i</m>, the 
        kinetic energy term  
      </p>

      <me>
        \tfrac12 (\vec{x}')^{\!T} M \vec{x}'
      </me>

      <p>
        is exactly 
        <m>\tfrac12 ( m_1 x_1'^2 + m_2 x_2'^2 + \cdots )</m>.  
        The stiffness matrix <m>K</m> encodes how the springs resist 
        displacement. The potential energy stored in the system is
      </p>

      <me>
        \tfrac12 \vec{x}^{T} K \vec{x}.
      </me>

      <p>
        Off-diagonal entries of <m>K</m> represent coupling between masses 
        (neighboring displacements affect each other), while diagonal entries 
        reflect how strongly the system resists stretching at each mass 
        location.  
        This matches the physical interpretation provided alongside the 
        construction of <m>M</m> and <m>K</m> in the text.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>



  <!-- PROBLEM 2 -->
  <exercise xml:id="secondorderopennew2">
    <title>Understanding Normal Modes Without Calculation</title>

    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose a three-mass undamped spring system is modeled by 
        <m>M \vec{x}'' = K \vec{x}</m>.  
        Let the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of <m>M^{-1}K</m> be 
        <m>(-\omega_1^2, \vec{v}_1)</m>, <m>(-\omega_2^2, \vec{v}_2)</m>, 
        and <m>(-\omega_3^2, \vec{v}_3)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Explain, in words and without doing any computation, what the motion 
        <em>looks like</em> when the system is started exactly in the shape of 
        the eigenvector <m>\vec{v}_2</m> with some initial velocity along 
        <m>\vec{v}_2</m>.  
        Why does no other mode appear in the motion?
      </p>
    </statement>

    <solution>
      <p>
        If the initial displacement and velocity are both multiples of 
        <m>\vec{v}_2</m>, then the system begins in the exact shape of the 
        <em>second normal mode</em>.  
        Each eigenpair produces an independent 
        oscillatory solution <m>\vec{v}_i e^{\pm i\omega_i t}</m>, and that 
        the general motion is a linear combination of these normal modes.
      </p>

      <p>
        Because <m>\vec{v}_1, \vec{v}_2, \vec{v}_3</m> form a basis of 
        independent modes, any displacement can be written as a combination 
        of them.  
        But if the initial state lies <em>entirely</em> in the direction of 
        <m>\vec{v}_2</m>, there is no component of <m>\vec{v}_1</m> or 
        <m>\vec{v}_3</m> in the initial condition.  
        Therefore the solution must remain a pure oscillation of the form
      </p>

      <me>
        \vec{x}(t) = A \vec{v}_2 \cos(\omega_2 t)
                    + B \vec{v}_2 \sin(\omega_2 t),
      </me>

      <p>
        with frequency <m>\omega_2</m>.  
        No other frequency can appear because there is no component of the 
        initial state aligned with the other eigenvectors.  
        This is exactly the decoupling property of normal modes.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


